{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17475058","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17475058"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:28:19+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:28:19+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12508"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12508","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12508"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.68,0.15,0.11,0.02,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5014"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106460"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5014","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5014"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12508"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88919"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"42"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2316"},{"type":"tags","id":"3549"},{"type":"tags","id":"3696"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"4945"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11631"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8305"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8616"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12298"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43337"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43889"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106460","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/106460"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 5-year-old boy presents to the General Practice clinic with his parent with complaints of intermittent abdominal pain and loose stools for the past three months. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. His immunisations are up to date. His parent reports that he passes stools 2-3 times daily and that there have been some greasy residue marks on his underwear and that he\u0027s been teased by other children at school for having smelly stools. Despite a good appetite, he has not gained weight in the last six months. There is no recent history of travel or consumption of contaminated water. He has had three episodes of bronchitis in the past year, each resolving with oral antibiotics. On examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 101/min, blood pressure 94/61 mmHg, respiratory rate 23/min, SpO2 97% on room air, and temperature 37.1\u00b0C. His weight is around the 15th percentile and height at the 25th percentile. The remainder of the examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin: 115 g/L (115-155)\u003Cbr /\u003EWhite cell count: 10.5 x 10^9/L (5.0-15.0)\u003Cbr /\u003EPlatelets: 280 x 10^9/L (150-400)\u003Cbr /\u003ESodium: 138 mmol/L (135-145)\u003Cbr /\u003EPotassium: 3.8 mmol/L (3.5-5.0)\u003Cbr /\u003EChloride: 105 mmol/L (95-105)\u003Cbr /\u003EBicarbonate: 22 mmol/L (22-29)\u003Cbr /\u003EAlbumin: 32 g/L (35-50)\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Perform a sweat chloride test","Initiate a gluten-free diet","Order stool microscopy and culture","Commence empiric treatment for giardiasis","Refer for upper gastrointestinal endoscopy"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation of this 5-year-old boy is suggestive of cystic fibrosis (CF). The most appropriate next step in management is to \u003Cstrong\u003Eperform a sweat chloride test\u003C/strong\u003E, which is the gold standard for diagnosing CF. This test measures the concentration of chloride in sweat, which is elevated in individuals with CF due to impaired function of the cystic fibrosis transmembrane conductance regulator (CFTR) protein.  Whilst most patients in Australia would have had a Guthrie newborn screening test (heel prick test) at birth, up to 5% of patients can be missed on this test.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe patient presents with several features consistent with CF, including chronic abdominal pain, foul smelling and greasy stools, failure to thrive despite good appetite, and recurrent respiratory infections. The low albumin level also supports malabsorption.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInitiating a gluten-free diet\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate if coeliac disease was suspected. While coeliac disease can present with similar gastrointestinal symptoms and failure to thrive, it typically doesn\u0027t cause recurrent respiratory infections. Additionally, a gluten-free diet should only be started after confirming the diagnosis through serological testing and duodenal biopsy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOrdering stool microscopy and culture\u003C/strong\u003E could be helpful in ruling out infectious causes of chronic diarrhoea. However, given the constellation of symptoms including respiratory issues and the duration of symptoms, an infectious cause is less likely. If the sweat chloride test is negative, this might be a reasonable next step.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECommencing empiric treatment for giardiasis\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate without evidence of exposure or compatible stool studies. While giardiasis can cause chronic diarrhoea and malabsorption, it doesn\u0027t explain the respiratory symptoms or the long-term failure to thrive.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReferring for upper gastrointestinal endoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E would be more appropriate if inflammatory bowel disease or coeliac disease were the primary suspicions. While these conditions can cause similar gastrointestinal symptoms, they don\u0027t typically cause recurrent respiratory infections.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf the sweat chloride test is positive or borderline, the next step would be to refer for genetic testing for CFTR mutations.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cystic fibrosis can present atypically with variable severity, requiring a high index of suspicion for diagnosis.","The sweat chloride test is the best option for diagnosing cystic fibrosis, but genetic testing can be useful in certain cases.","Pancreatic insufficiency in cystic fibrosis results in malabsorption and failure to thrive."],"references":["Yu E, Sharma S. Cystic Fibrosis. [Updated 2022 Aug 8]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2022 Jan-."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88919"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12508"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88919","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/88919"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-20T00:58:41+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-20T00:58:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5014"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106460"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"typ